content.description: Crack climb your way through the overhanging dihedral crack to an easy topout.
content.location: the obvious crack in the boulder

content.description: The right dihedral on the beerholder side of the boulder. I remember crimps, a weird undercling, really tough feet, and a slopey topout. I also remember it being really good.I don't remember if we started sitting or standing, but it felt about V6. I do think it’s a sit start.
content.location: The right dihedral on the beerholder side of the boulder

content.description: Sit start in the monster jug under the prow, climb up the good holds to a fun topout
content.location: Monster jug under a steep prow Go left on the good holds instead of going right on the bad ones that make up "Beerholder Right"

content.description: Sit down and match on a crimp below a steep line of right trending crimps. Climb them out towards bigger holds to the right. Pumpy topout, athletic movement. This is probably the best line on the boulder.
content.location: Under the overhang on the north side (cliff side) of the boulder

content.description: Start as for Beerholder, but at the mid face crimp head up holds to the right utilizing a really high heel hook and stronk crimp strength.

The Owl Pellet is a large and highly featured boulder just off the approach trail to Owl's Head Cliff. If you're willing to brave the swamp with pads on your back you will be rewarded with beautifuly sculpted granite holds, nice landings, and clean rock.
